WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.360
Hi, my name is Shannon Pileggi, and here are three reasons why you should take the What

00:00:11.360 --> 00:00:16.360
They Forgot to Teach You About R project-oriented workflows with Git and GitHub workshop.

00:00:16.360 --> 00:00:20.680
Number one, I'm really excited to co-lead this workshop with David for the second year

00:00:20.680 --> 00:00:21.680
in a row.

00:00:21.680 --> 00:00:26.160
David is a solutions engineer at Posit, and I'm a lead data scientist with the Prostate

00:00:26.160 --> 00:00:28.840
Cancer Clinical Trials Consortium.

00:00:28.840 --> 00:00:32.439
David and I work really well together, and we learn from each other.

00:00:32.439 --> 00:00:38.240
Our diverse perspectives really benefit the participants in this course.

00:00:38.240 --> 00:00:43.240
Number two, the spirit of the What They Forgot to Teach You About R workshop are strategies

00:00:43.240 --> 00:00:49.200
to improve the quality of your R life via project workflows and version control with

00:00:49.200 --> 00:00:50.759
Git and GitHub.

00:00:50.759 --> 00:00:56.759
These are paradigms that you can benefit from no matter what stage you are in in your career.

00:00:57.680 --> 00:01:02.439
Lastly, the What They Forgot to Teach You About R content is solid.

00:01:02.439 --> 00:01:07.959
This workshop has actually been instructed since 2018, so the course content has a really

00:01:07.959 --> 00:01:12.959
strong foundation that's assessed every year to be updated for new developments.

00:01:12.959 --> 00:01:15.599
So I really hope you can join us at Posit Conf.

00:01:15.599 --> 00:01:17.519
Hi, I'm David Alja.

00:01:17.519 --> 00:01:20.760
I'm a solutions engineer at Posit.

00:01:20.760 --> 00:01:24.919
Sometimes I describe that as a role focused on helping data scientists get their ideas

00:01:24.919 --> 00:01:25.919
into production.

00:01:25.919 --> 00:01:31.919
But in practice, what that means is that a lot of the time I'm focused on the parts of

00:01:31.919 --> 00:01:36.680
working with R that aren't about writing R code, but more about what it looks like to

00:01:36.680 --> 00:01:42.680
manage it, to share it, and to help it answer questions for lots of different user groups.

00:01:42.680 --> 00:01:46.279
So the reason I think you should take What They Forgot to Teach You About R is because

00:01:46.279 --> 00:01:51.040
I think it helps, it's an opportunity to help you learn some of the software engineering

00:01:51.040 --> 00:01:57.959
fundamentals that aren't really going to come up in other kinds of R-focused programming

00:01:57.959 --> 00:01:58.959
classes.

00:01:58.959 --> 00:02:04.559
I know that when I started learning R programming, I was very much focused on how do I extract

00:02:04.559 --> 00:02:09.639
the data from this HTML table, and not as focused on questions like what is it going

00:02:09.639 --> 00:02:14.320
to look like to work on this project again in another year, or what's it going to look

00:02:14.320 --> 00:02:17.639
like to collaborate with this project with someone else.

00:02:17.639 --> 00:02:22.279
And I think that What They Forgot is an excellent venue for learning that kind of thing, so

00:02:22.279 --> 00:02:22.880
I hope to see you there.

